		<item>
		<title>Makhura believed digital revolution could address Gauteng unemployment crisis</title>
		<link>http://www.newspages.co.za/makhura-believed-digital-revolution-could-address-gauteng-unemployment-crisis/</link>
		<pubDate>Wed, 07 Mar 2018 14:12:58 +0000</pubDate>
		<dc:creator><![CDATA[Benice Burger]]></dc:creator>
				<category><![CDATA[Adslive]]></category>
		<category><![CDATA[Business]]></category>
		<category><![CDATA[Dotcom]]></category>
		<category><![CDATA[Education]]></category>
		<category><![CDATA[Gauteng – Government]]></category>
		<category><![CDATA[Government South Africa]]></category>
		<category><![CDATA[Government Success Stories]]></category>
		<category><![CDATA[Social Media]]></category>
		<category><![CDATA[South Africa]]></category>
		<category><![CDATA[South Africa - SADC]]></category>
		<category><![CDATA[Speeches]]></category>
		<category><![CDATA[Technology]]></category>
		<category><![CDATA[crisis]]></category>
		<category><![CDATA[David Makhura]]></category>
		<category><![CDATA[Digital]]></category>
		<category><![CDATA[digital economy]]></category>
		<category><![CDATA[digital revolution]]></category>
		<category><![CDATA[digital skills]]></category>
		<category><![CDATA[digital skills training]]></category>
		<category><![CDATA[employment opportunities]]></category>
		<category><![CDATA[entrepreneurship]]></category>
		<category><![CDATA[Gauteng]]></category>
		<category><![CDATA[Gauteng Innovation Hub]]></category>
		<category><![CDATA[Gauteng Premier]]></category>
		<category><![CDATA[ourth industrial revolution]]></category>
		<category><![CDATA[Premier David Makhura]]></category>
		<category><![CDATA[Silicon Valley]]></category>
		<category><![CDATA[tech-preneurs]]></category>
		<category><![CDATA[technology]]></category>
		<category><![CDATA[Tshepo 1-million programme]]></category>
		<category><![CDATA[unemployment]]></category>
		<category><![CDATA[unemployment crisis]]></category>
		<category><![CDATA[youth]]></category>

		<guid isPermaLink="false">http://www.newspages.co.za/?p=10494</guid>
		<description><![CDATA[<img width="210" height="158" src="http://www.newspages.co.za/wp-content/uploads/2018/03/6-210x158.jpg" class="webfeedsFeaturedVisual wp-post-image" alt="" style="float: left; margin-right: 5px;" />
Gauteng Premier David Makhura (Madelene Cronje/MG)
<p>Gauteng Premier David Makhura has placed his hopes on the advent of the fourth industrial revolution to provide solutions for the province’s youth unemployment crisis.</p>
<p>Makhura delivered his state of the province address at the Gauteng legislature on Monday where he said nearly 2-million young people in the province were unemployed, not in schooling or receiving any sort of training.</p>
<p>The interventions proposed by the province appeared heavily centred on taking advantage of the digital economy to create employment opportunities.</p>
<p>“As part of addressing structural youth unemployment we are aligning our education and training to meet the needs of our new economy,” Makhura said.</p>
<p>“We have a partnership with technology companies to train young people in digital skills so they can take full advantage of employment and entrepreneurship opportunities in the digital economy,” he added.</p>
<p>Makhura said the focus on tech and digital skills had already been started from a basic education level, where he said the province was the leader in digital skills training nationally</p>
<p>He also announced plans to improve the effectiveness of the Gauteng Innovation Hub, through collaborations with technology entrepreneurs who would mentor young tech entrepreneurs.</p>
<p>“This year we will sent 20 tech-preneurs to Silicon Valley where they will join the rest of the world so that we too can be at the forefront of the digital revolution,” Makhura said.</p>
<p>To date Gauteng government’s flagship Tshepo 1-million programme has benefited more than 460 000 young people since its inception in 2015.</p>
<p>The programme, which is a joint project between the public and private sectors, aims to empower 1 million young people through skills training and job placement and entrepreneurship development.</p>
<p> </p>
<p>Source: https://mg.co.za/article/2018-02-26-makhura-believed-digital-revolution-could-address-gauteng-unemployment-crisis</p>
]]></description>
				<content:encoded><![CDATA[<img width="210" height="158" src="http://www.newspages.co.za/wp-content/uploads/2018/03/6-210x158.jpg" class="webfeedsFeaturedVisual wp-post-image" alt="" style="float: left; margin-right: 5px;" /><h6><img class="alignnone wp-image-10495 size-large" src="http://www.newspages.co.za/wp-content/uploads/2018/03/6.1-640x360.jpg" alt="" width="640" height="360" srcset="http://www.newspages.co.za/wp-content/uploads/2018/03/6.1-640x360.jpg 640w, http://www.newspages.co.za/wp-content/uploads/2018/03/6.1-300x169.jpg 300w, http://www.newspages.co.za/wp-content/uploads/2018/03/6.1-16x9.jpg 16w, http://www.newspages.co.za/wp-content/uploads/2018/03/6.1-32x18.jpg 32w, http://www.newspages.co.za/wp-content/uploads/2018/03/6.1-28x16.jpg 28w, http://www.newspages.co.za/wp-content/uploads/2018/03/6.1-56x32.jpg 56w, http://www.newspages.co.za/wp-content/uploads/2018/03/6.1-64x36.jpg 64w, http://www.newspages.co.za/wp-content/uploads/2018/03/6.1-712x400.jpg 712w, http://www.newspages.co.za/wp-content/uploads/2018/03/6.1.jpg 800w" sizes="(max-width: 640px) 100vw, 640px" /><br />
Gauteng Premier David Makhura (Madelene Cronje/MG)</h6>
<p>Gauteng Premier David Makhura has placed his hopes on the advent of the fourth industrial revolution to provide solutions for the province’s youth unemployment crisis.</p>
<p>Makhura delivered his state of the province address at the Gauteng legislature on Monday where he said nearly 2-million young people in the province were unemployed, not in schooling or receiving any sort of training.</p>
<p>The interventions proposed by the province appeared heavily centred on taking advantage of the digital economy to create employment opportunities.</p>
<p>“As part of addressing structural youth unemployment we are aligning our education and training to meet the needs of our new economy,” Makhura said.</p>
<p>“We have a partnership with technology companies to train young people in digital skills so they can take full advantage of employment and entrepreneurship opportunities in the digital economy,” he added.</p>
<p>Makhura said the focus on tech and digital skills had already been started from a basic education level, where he said the province was the leader in digital skills training nationally</p>
<p>He also announced plans to improve the effectiveness of the Gauteng Innovation Hub, through collaborations with technology entrepreneurs who would mentor young tech entrepreneurs.</p>
<p>“This year we will sent 20 tech-preneurs to Silicon Valley where they will join the rest of the world so that we too can be at the forefront of the digital revolution,” Makhura said.</p>
<p>To date Gauteng government’s flagship Tshepo 1-million programme has benefited more than 460 000 young people since its inception in 2015.</p>
<p>The programme, which is a joint project between the public and private sectors, aims to empower 1 million young people through skills training and job placement and entrepreneurship development.</p>
<p><strong> </strong></p>
<p><strong>Source: </strong><a href="https://mg.co.za/article/2018-02-26-makhura-believed-digital-revolution-could-address-gauteng-unemployment-crisis"><strong>https://mg.co.za/article/2018-02-26-makhura-believed-digital-revolution-could-address-gauteng-unemployment-crisis</strong></a></p>
]]></content:encoded>
