		<item>
		<title>Jo’burg police launch traffic fine email campaign</title>
		<link>http://www.newspages.co.za/joburg-police-launch-traffic-fine-email-campaign/</link>
		<pubDate>Wed, 27 Sep 2017 07:54:48 +0000</pubDate>
		<dc:creator><![CDATA[Benice Burger]]></dc:creator>
				<category><![CDATA[Gauteng – Government]]></category>
		<category><![CDATA[Motoring]]></category>
		<category><![CDATA[South Africa]]></category>
		<category><![CDATA[Johannesburg Metropolitan Police Department]]></category>
		<category><![CDATA[Road Traffic Infringement Agency]]></category>

		<guid isPermaLink="false">http://www.newspages.co.za/?p=9758</guid>
		<description><![CDATA[<img width="210" height="158" src="http://www.newspages.co.za/wp-content/uploads/2017/09/Traffic-Fine-210x158.jpg" class="webfeedsFeaturedVisual wp-post-image" alt="" style="float: left; margin-right: 5px;" srcset="http://www.newspages.co.za/wp-content/uploads/2017/09/Traffic-Fine-210x158.jpg 210w, http://www.newspages.co.za/wp-content/uploads/2017/09/Traffic-Fine-16x11.jpg 16w" sizes="(max-width: 210px) 100vw, 210px" /><p>JPSA chairman Howard Dembovsky has warned Gauteng motorists about an SMS and email campaign which targets individuals with “stagnated” traffic fines. Dembovsky said a company called Syntell, which contracts services to traffic authorities, has launched the campaign which it states is on behalf of the Road Traffic Infringement Agency (RTIA).</p>
<p>It seeks to “rake in monies applicable to stagnated traffic fines issued by the Johannesburg Metropolitan Police Department”, said Dembovsky. “Syntell previously did similar with traffic fines issued by the Ekurhuleni Metropolitan Police Department in terms of the Criminal Procedure Act, against which a national directive… ordering the withdrawal of stagnated matters exists,” he said.</p>
<p>Infringements</p>
<p>The latest email campaign is sent from a “RTIA@trafficnotification.co.za” address, and contains recipients’ names, ID numbers, vehicle details, and a list of outstanding AARTO infringement notices.</p>
<p>“In numerous instances, the fines listed date back five years, to 2012, when the JMPD ceased unlawfully violating Section 30(1) of the AARTO Act by posting bogus AARTO infringement notices it had captured on its systems since April 2010 by ordinary domestic mail.”</p>
<p>Dembovsky said it appears the RTIA is waiting for alleged infringers to make written representations to it in order to have the stagnated fines withdrawn or cancelled. This is done with the “apparent hope that less-informed motorists will pay these stagnated fines”.</p>
<p>“It adopted the same tactic in the previous matter where the JMPD acted unlawfully – until the JMPD and the RTIA found themselves being threatened with litigation if they did not administratively cancel all of the outstanding unlawful fines the JMPD had issued,” said Dembovsky.</p>
<p>He said that most of the infringement notices referred to in the emails have stagnated, and the associated threats were extortive.</p>
<p>“The threat which repeatedly appears in these emails stating that you will not be able to renew your vehicle or driving licence whilst an enforcement order is outstanding is, while not patently untrue, not only extortive in nature, but is an empty threat since no enforcement order may be lawfully issued on an arbitrary basis.”</p>
<p>Source: https://mybroadband.co.za/news/motoring/230553-johannesburg-police-launch-traffic-fine-email-campaign-to-get-you-to-pay-up.html</p>
]]></description>
				<content:encoded><![CDATA[<img width="210" height="158" src="http://www.newspages.co.za/wp-content/uploads/2017/09/Traffic-Fine-210x158.jpg" class="webfeedsFeaturedVisual wp-post-image" alt="" style="float: left; margin-right: 5px;" srcset="http://www.newspages.co.za/wp-content/uploads/2017/09/Traffic-Fine-210x158.jpg 210w, http://www.newspages.co.za/wp-content/uploads/2017/09/Traffic-Fine-16x11.jpg 16w" sizes="(max-width: 210px) 100vw, 210px" /><p>JPSA chairman Howard Dembovsky has warned Gauteng motorists about an SMS and email campaign which targets individuals with “stagnated” traffic fines. Dembovsky said a company called Syntell, which contracts services to traffic authorities, has launched the campaign which it states is on behalf of the Road Traffic Infringement Agency (RTIA).</p>
